ht|h|fp|1|cp|2|at|Do you know all you need to know about this strange animal named Redouble?

If your answer is "no", just keep reading. If you think inversely, well… you can't be damaged by reading it also.

The historical usage of redouble in modern bridge was for penalty purposes – a try to enlarge the score by the 
side that bought the contract and was doubled by the opponents. 

It was, in a sense: "If you think that I can't make my contract, I will show you what I think about that by redoubling your double".

About 60-70 years ago, a new idea has been originated: instead of ^*B "I can make my bid" ^*Nit was converted into: 
^*B"I believe I can defeat you whatever contract you may bid".|
^*N
ht|r|fp|1|cp|2|at|^pHere is the basic form of redoubling:|

ht|s|cs|1|at|^o{|ia|   1sx!r|at|}|

ht|x|fp|1|cp|2|at|^pWhat does North show by this bid? 

North shows a hand worth at least 10-11 points, usually denies support for opener's major, ^*Balways ^*Ndenies four-card support.|
