nt||

ht|f|fp|1|cp|2|at|Why? 

This is simply because:

1. When you redouble to show the intention to eventually double every contract the opponents may bid, it would be 
    unreasonable for you to have a good support for your partner's suit. That is since having that support will leave 
    you with an insufficient number of cards in the other suits for doubling the opponents' contract.  

2. Having support for partner's suit may make the redouble much less profitable, or not at all, because your 
    partnership may have a game.

3. When you have a fit in a major suit, especially when it is a nine-card fit, there is a very good chance for the 
    opponents to have a good fit in the other major. In those cases redoubling may prove to be a waste of time 
    as it may give the opponents the opportunity to find out if they have a heart fit. Facing such a fit would make a 
    punishment impossible in most cases. Show support with support!

One more important note, easy to forget: the redouble always promises a second bid. 

Therefore, the opener (South in our example) may pass a possible bid by East, leaving the redoubler with the option to double every bid made by East.

Do you always have to redouble with 10+ points and with no support for partner's suit?

The answer is no! 

The redouble has a particular meaning and when your hand does not meet the requirements, you should look for alternatives.|
